1
00:00:00,163 --> 00:00:05,268
The neo-Darwinian
theory of evolution says

2
00:00:05,268 --> 00:00:07,904
that all life on
earth arose from a common

3
00:00:07,904 --> 00:00:10,907
ancestor by way of random mutations to

4
00:00:10,907 --> 00:00:14,444
genes preserved by
natural selection. Organisms

5
00:00:14,444 --> 00:00:17,413
with beneficial
mutations produced more offspring

6
00:00:17,413 --> 00:00:21,050
than those with
deleterious or damaging mutations.

7
00:00:21,050 --> 00:00:22,952
Some beneficial mutations provided

8
00:00:22,952 --> 00:00:26,289
adaptations to new or
changed environments, producing

9
00:00:26,289 --> 00:00:29,158
new kinds of
organisms. In order to get extra

10
00:00:29,158 --> 00:00:32,762
new information to
build more complex organisms,

11
00:00:32,762 --> 00:00:37,900
existing genes must have been
duplicated and then mutated into something useful.

12
00:00:37,900 --> 00:00:40,803
Right, but
population geneticist J.B.S. Haldane

13
00:00:40,803 --> 00:00:43,639
realized that when a
beneficial mutation occurs

14
00:00:43,639 --> 00:00:46,709
in a population,
the number of copies of that

15
00:00:46,709 --> 00:00:50,380
mutation must increase
over time for the population

16
00:00:50,380 --> 00:00:53,149
to progress evolutionarily. It has to

17
00:00:53,149 --> 00:00:56,953
substitute for the
non-mutated genes in the population.

18
00:00:56,953 --> 00:00:59,422
But the rate at which this can happen is

19
00:00:59,422 --> 00:01:03,326
limited. Haldane
realized that there hasn't been enough

20
00:01:03,326 --> 00:01:06,596
time to accumulate
enough beneficial mutations

21
00:01:06,596 --> 00:01:09,832
to transform an
ape-like creature into a human.

22
00:01:09,832 --> 00:01:12,402
This became known as
Haldane's dilemma, and he

23
00:01:12,402 --> 00:01:15,371
explained it like
this. Imagine a population of

24
00:01:15,371 --> 00:01:19,042
100,000 ape-like
creatures 10 million years ago,

25
00:01:19,042 --> 00:01:21,544
more than the
supposed time since the last common

26
00:01:21,544 --> 00:01:24,847
ancestor of humans
and apes. Suppose a male and

27
00:01:24,847 --> 00:01:27,850
a female both
received a mutation so beneficial

28
00:01:27,850 --> 00:01:33,489
that they survived
while the 99,998 all died

29
00:01:33,489 --> 00:01:37,026
out. Then they had
enough offspring to replenish the

30
00:01:37,026 --> 00:01:40,863
population of
100,000 in one generation. If

31
00:01:40,863 --> 00:01:44,500
this repeated every 20
years for 10 million years,

32
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:47,904
there would be
500,000 beneficial mutations added

33
00:01:47,904 --> 00:01:52,809
to the population. This
amounts to only 0.02% of the

34
00:01:52,809 --> 00:01:56,045
human genome. Even the old myth of 1-2%

35
00:01:56,045 --> 00:01:59,315
difference between
human and chimp DNA wouldn't work.

36
00:01:59,315 --> 00:02:01,284
But we know the
difference is actually at least

37
00:02:01,284 --> 00:02:05,922
5%, or as much as 15%.
We did an entire episode on

38
00:02:05,922 --> 00:02:11,294
this subject titled "Chimp to Human
DNA, Less Similar Than Previously Reported."

39
00:02:11,294 --> 00:02:13,596
Obviously Haldane
put forward an incredibly

40
00:02:13,596 --> 00:02:16,799
unlikely scenario
here. He calculated a more

41
00:02:16,799 --> 00:02:19,902
realistic scenario
would be one beneficial

42
00:02:19,902 --> 00:02:24,574
mutation about every
300 generations on average

43
00:02:24,574 --> 00:02:31,681
for a total of 1,667 beneficial
mutations over 10 million years. That's nothing.

44
00:02:31,681 --> 00:02:34,083
Definitely not enough. Even if the 1%

45
00:02:34,083 --> 00:02:37,453
difference were true,
we'd need 30 million beneficial

46
00:02:37,453 --> 00:02:40,189
mutations, which
would take about 9 billion

47
00:02:40,189 --> 00:02:44,560
generations, or 180
billion years. That's about

48
00:02:44,560 --> 00:02:49,031
13 times the supposed age of the
universe according to the Big Bang Theory.

